{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503220","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503220"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:57:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:57:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1946"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1946","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1946"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.74,0.02,0.04,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1946"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91642"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1946","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1946"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1946"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75212"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1482"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31287"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91642","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/91642"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 54-year-old man is admitted to hospital for an acute exacerbation of his chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD). He has a 45 pack-year smoking history. He drinks about three cans of beer a week. His medications include salbutamol inhaler prn and tiotropium inhaler once daily.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his blood pressure is 128/86 mmHg, pulse 100/min and temperature 37.6 C. The only abnormal findings are those related to his COPD. He is clinically euvolaemic and there are no visual field deficits. His electrolytes, urea and creatinine (EUC) test on admission reveals a sodium level of 126 mmol/L (normal 135-145 mmol/L). All other values are within the normal range. There are no other recent EUC results. His serum osmolality is hypotonic (270mEq/L) and urine sodium is 44mmol/L (normal \u0026lt;20mmol/L).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for the laboratory findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chronic kidney disease","Small cell lung cancer","Cirrhosis of the liver","Congestive heart failure","Pituitary adenoma"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient is likely to have syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion (SIADH) due to his hypotonic hyponatraemia, clinically euvolaemic volume status and elevated urinary sodium level, suggesting a renal cause . The underlying cause of his SIADH is most likely a\u003Cstrong\u003E small cell lung cancer\u003C/strong\u003E as part of a paraneoplastic syndrome. This is in context of his extensive smoking history. Small cell lung cancers out of all the lung cancer are particularly known for causing many endocrinopathies. There is nothing in the stem to suggest chronic kidney disease, such as an unremarkable creatinine on the EUC and no medical history of hypertension or diabetes mellitus as predisposing conditions. Additionally, in both cirrhosis of the liver and congestive heart failure, the patient would be expected to present with a hypervolaemic hyponatraemia, as well as a normal urine sodium i.e. \u0026lt;20mmol/L, because they are both extra-renal causes of hyponatraemia. Whilst pituitary adenoma could also result in SIADH, it is less likely as the patient does not have any visual field disturbances, such as bitemporal hemianopia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bronchogenic neoplasms are an important cause of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion (paraneoplastic syndrome)."],"references":["Grant P, Ayuk J, Bouloux P-M, et al. The diagnosis and management of inpatient hyponatraemia and SIADH. Eur J Clin Invest 2015; 45:888-94."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75212"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1946"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75212","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75212"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-16T07:34:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-16T07:34:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1946"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91642"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting 